FAQs
1. What are the language requirements for studying in Ireland?
Most programs in Irish universities are taught in English. Proficiency in English is typically required, and you may need to submit TOEFL or IELTS scores. Some universities also offer language preparation courses for students who need to improve their English skills.

2. Are there scholarships available for international students in Ireland?
Yes, many Irish universities and government programs offer scholarships to international students based on academic merit, financial need, or other criteria. These scholarships can help cover tuition fees and living expenses.

3. How much does it cost to live in Ireland as a student?
The cost of living in Ireland can vary depending on the city and lifestyle. On average, students might spend between €700 to €1,200 per month on accommodation, food, transportation, and leisure activities. Dublin tends to be more expensive than other cities like Galway or Cork.
